Today, we officially kicked off Module 1.1: Cyber Security Linux – Introduction to Computers with Darryl. It was a deep dive into the fundamentals of computing, and while some of it felt familiar, there were plenty of new concepts that made me think differently about how computers work on a fundamental level.

We started with firmware and the differences between 32-bit and 64-bit architectures. I always knew these terms existed, but breaking them down in detail helped me understand why they matter—especially when dealing with operating systems and software compatibility.

One of the more interesting parts of the discussion was about interfaces like PAIA, SCSI, and SATA—terms I had heard before but never really explored. It was eye-opening to see how these technologies connect different components and evolved.

We wrapped up with a comparison between GUI (Graphical User Interface) and CLI (Command Line Interface). I’m comfortable with a GUI, but I know CLI is where real power users operate so I’m looking forward to getting more hands-on with Linux commands in the future.

Today’s session gave me a new appreciation for the foundational elements of computers. Understanding how everything connects—hardware, storage, memory, and interfaces feels like putting together pieces of a puzzle. This knowledge will be crucial as we move further into cybersecurity and Linux system administration.
